Besides uptake, efflux was another important factor determining the intracellular accumulation of CDs. In the present study, significant elimination of CDs was observed for both algae pre-exposed to 1 and 10 mg L−1 of CDs, respectively (Fig. 6
                        ). Although their elimination was independent of [CDs]cell, significant difference (p < 0.05) was observed between P. donghaiense and P. micans. Accordingly, ∼58% of the CDs accumulated in P. micans was retained at the end of 48-h depuration, whereas 70.2–79.4% was retained in P. donghaiense. The decrease of [CDs]cell with depuration time was then simulated by Eq. (2). The value of K
                        e thus obtained was in the range of 0.0047–0.0067 h−1 and 0.0108–0.0109 h−1 for P. donghaiense and P. micans, respectively. The efflux of CDs from both algae observed in the present study was much lower than what was observed in neural cells (PC12 and RSC96) (Zhou et al., 2014). In the latter case, CDs were actively exocytosed with a half-life of 2 h and approximately 90% of the cellularly accumulated CDs was eliminated after 48 h. The discrepancy between this study and ours further supports the hypothesis of cell specific efflux of nanoparticles proposed by Yang et al. (2014). The longer retention of CDs in the dinoflagellates with a half-life of 63.6–147.5 h may further increase their toxicity. Based on the uptake and efflux kinetics results, the higher accumulation of CDs in P. donghaiense than in P. micans as observed in the toxicity experiment above was a combined result of the higher uptake and lower elimination of CDs by the former algal species.
